  "prompt": "What are some popular drink/shots to get at the bar?",
  "response": "Okay, let's break down some popular bar drinks and shots, categorized for easier browsing:\n\n**Popular Cocktails (Drinks)**\n\n*   **Classics (Tried and True):**\n\n    *   **Old Fashioned:** Whiskey, sugar, bitters, orange peel.  Strong and spirit-forward.\n    *   **Martini:** Gin or vodka, dry vermouth, olive or lemon twist.  Dry, sophisticated, and customizable.\n    *   **Manhattan:** Whiskey, sweet vermouth, bitters, cherry.  Similar to an Old Fashioned but with vermouth adding sweetness and complexity.\n    *   **Daiquiri:** Rum, lime juice, simple syrup.  Simple, refreshing, and a good test of a bartender's skills.  (Don't confuse this with the frozen variety).\n    *   **Margarita:** Tequila, lime juice, Cointreau (or triple sec), salt rim (optional).  Tangy, refreshing, and great for warm weather.\n    *   **Mojito:** Rum, mint, lime, sugar, soda water.  Minty, refreshing, and Cuban-inspired.\n    *   **Whiskey Sour:** Whiskey, lemon juice, simple syrup, egg white (optional).  A balance of sweet and sour with a frothy texture.\n    *   **Negroni:** Gin, Campari, sweet vermouth.  Bitter, complex, and Italian.\n    *   **Moscow Mule:** Vodka, ginger beer, lime juice.  Served in a copper mug, spicy and refreshing.\n    *   **Long Island Iced Tea:** Vodka, gin, rum, tequila, triple sec, lemon juice, cola.  Potent and sweet.\n    *   **Cosmopolitan:** Vodka, cranberry juice, Cointreau, lime juice.  Tart, fruity, and popular.\n\n*   **Fruity & Sweet:**\n\n    *   **Pina Colada:** Rum, pineapple juice, coconut cream.  Tropical and creamy.\n    *   **Strawberry Daiquiri:** Rum, strawberries, lime juice, simple syrup.\n    *   **Sex on the Beach:** Vodka, peach schnapps, cranberry juice, orange juice.\n    *   **Midori Sour:** Midori melon liqueur, lemon juice, simple syrup.\n    *   **Mai Tai:** Rum, orgeat syrup, orange curacao, lime juice. Tropical and complex.\n\n*   **Spirit-Forward & Boozy:**\n\n    *   **Sazerac:** Rye whiskey, absinthe, Peychaud's Bitters, sugar. New Orleans classic, anise flavor.\n    *   **Rob Roy:** Scotch whisky, sweet vermouth, bitters. Scotch version of a Manhattan.\n\n**Popular Shots**\n\n*   **Simple & Classic:**\n\n    *   **Tequila Shot:** Tequila, lime, salt.  The classic.\n    *   **Whiskey Shot:** Straight whiskey (bourbon, rye, Scotch).\n    *   **Vodka Shot:** Straight vodka (often chilled).\n    *   **Rum Shot:** Straight rum (white or dark).\n    *   **Jager Bomb:** J\u00e4germeister dropped into Red Bull.  Energy drink and herbal liqueur.\n\n*   **Sweet & Fun:**\n\n    *   **B-52:** Layered Kahlua, Baileys Irish Cream, and Grand Marnier.  Looks cool.\n    *   **Lemon Drop:** Vodka, lemon juice, simple syrup, sugared lemon wedge.\n    *   **Kamikaze:** Vodka, triple sec, lime juice.\n    *   **Washington Apple:** Crown Royal, Apple Pucker, cranberry juice.\n    *   **Buttery Nipple:** Butterscotch schnapps, Baileys Irish Cream.  Sweet and creamy.\n    *   **Scooby Snack:** Midori, coconut rum, pineapple juice, and whipped cream.\n\n*   **Strong & Potent:**\n\n    *   **Irish Car Bomb:** Guinness, Baileys Irish Cream, Jameson Irish Whiskey (drop shot).  Controversial name, but a popular combination.\n    *   **Four Horsemen:** Jim Beam, Jack Daniels, Johnny Walker, Jameson.\n\n**Things to Consider When Choosing:**\n\n*   **Your Taste Preferences:** Do you like sweet, sour, bitter, strong, or refreshing?\n*   **The Bartender's Expertise:** Some cocktails are more complex and require a skilled bartender. If the bar is busy or the bartender seems inexperienced, stick to simpler drinks.\n*   **The Occasion:** A celebratory occasion might call for something fancier, while a casual night out might be better suited for a beer or a simple mixed drink.\n*   **The Bar's Speciality:** Some bars are known for their particular cocktails or ingredients. Don't be afraid to ask the bartender for recommendations based on what they do well.\n*   **Your Tolerance:** Pace yourself and know your limits. Don't be afraid to order a non-alcoholic drink or water between alcoholic beverages.\n\n**Important Tip:**  Don't be afraid to ask the bartender for recommendations!  They know their menu and can tailor suggestions to your taste.  Just tell them what you like (e.g., \"I like sweet drinks with rum,\" or \"I want something strong and whiskey-based\").  Also, tip your bartender!\n",
